Below is a **complete, self‑contained design** for a Lua‑C++ binding that lets a Lua script run a user‑supplied callback for every block in a BlockSci collection.  
The design focuses on **minimum per‑iteration overhead** while keeping the API pleasant for Lua users (think `pandas.DataFrame.apply` or `polars.lazy.map`).  

---  

## 1. High‑level Lua API (what the user sees)

```lua
local blocksi = require "blocksi"        -- loads the compiled C module

-- Open a chain (the heavy‑weight object that owns the block database)
local chain = blocksi.open("/path/to/bitcoin/chain")

-- -----------------------------------------------------------------
-- 1️⃣  Simple “for‑each” – run a Lua function on every block
-- -----------------------------------------------------------------
chain:for_each(function(block)          -- block is a lightweight userdata
    -- Example: print every 1 000 000th block
    if block.height % 1_000_000 == 0 then
        print("Reached block", block.height, block.hash)
    end
    -- The callback may *return* a boolean to stop early:
    --   return true   → stop iteration
    --   return false  → continue (default)
end)

-- -----------------------------------------------------------------
-- 2️⃣  Map – transform blocks into a Lua table (still fast)
-- -----------------------------------------------------------------
local heights = chain:map(function(b) return b.height end)
print("First 10 heights:", table.concat(heights, ", ", 1, 10))

-- -----------------------------------------------------------------
-- 3️⃣  Filter – keep only blocks that satisfy a predicate
-- -----------------------------------------------------------------
local filtered = chain:filter(function(b) return b.height % 2 == 0 end)
print("Even‑height blocks:", #filtered)   -- a Lua array of Block userdata
```

### What a **`Block`** looks like in Lua

```lua
-- block is a *userdata* that holds a pointer to the native C++ Block object.
-- It is cheap to create – the binding re‑uses the same userdata each callback.
print(block.height)            -- integer
print(block.hash)              -- 32‑byte binary string
print(block.timestamp)        -- UNIX epoch (seconds)
-- You can add more fields in the C++ side as needed.
```

*All* heavy work (the iterator, block parsing, hash calculation, etc.) stays in C++.  
Only the tiny Lua callback runs per block, and the binding re‑uses a single
userdata object to avoid allocations.

---  

## 2. Binding design – C++ / C side (single `.c` file)

Below is a **stand‑alone C source file** that can be compiled into a Lua module
(`blocksi.so` on Linux, `blocksi.dll` on Windows).  
It contains:

* Minimal C++ shim that pretends to be BlockSci (replace with the real
  BlockSci headers in production).
* The Lua userdata types:
  * `Chain` – owns the BlockSci database and creates iterators.
  * `BlockIter` – the internal iterator used by `for_each`, `map`, `filter`.
  * `Block` – a thin wrapper around a native `Block` object; **re‑used**
    for every callback to keep allocation‑free hot loops.
* Metatables that expose the read‑only fields (`height`, `hash`, `timestamp`).
* Three high‑level methods: `for_each`, `map`, `filter`.
* Helper functions that keep the per‑iteration cost low (no heap allocation,
  only a couple of Lua stack pushes).

```c
/*=====================================================================
   blocksi.c  –  Lua bindings for BlockSci (demo version)
   Compile (Linux):
       g++ -std=c++17 -shared -fPIC -O3 -I/usr/include/lua5.4 \
           -o blocksi.so blocksi.c -lstdc++
   (adjust include path / Lua version as needed)
  =====================================================================*/

extern "C" {
    #include <lua.h>
    #include <lauxlib.h>
    #include <lualib.h>
}
#include <cstddef>
#include <cstdint>
#include <cstring>
#include <vector>
#include <string>

/* --------------------------------------------------------------
   ----  Fake BlockSci API (replace with the real headers) ----
   -------------------------------------------------------------- */
struct Block {
    uint64_t height;
    std::array<unsigned char,32> hash;
    uint64_t timestamp;          // seconds since epoch
    // ... add any other fields you need
};
class BlockIterator {
public:
    BlockIterator(const std::string& db_path) : idx(0) {
        // In a real implementation you would open the DB and fill `blocks`.
        // Here we just generate dummy data to illustrate the binding.
        for (uint64_t i=0;i<800'000'000ull;i++) {
            Block b;
            b.height = i;
            for (int j=0;j<32;j++) b.hash[j] = (unsigned char)(i ^ j);
            b.timestamp = 1231006505 + i*600;   // genesis + 10‑min blocks
            blocks.push_back(b);
        }
    }
    bool has_next() const { return idx < blocks.size(); }
    const Block& next() { return blocks[idx++]; }
    void reset() { idx = 0; }
private:
    std::vector<Block> blocks;
    size_t idx;
};

/* --------------------------------------------------------------
   ----  Lua userdata structures  -------------------------------
   -------------------------------------------------------------- */
typedef struct {
    BlockIterator* iter;      // owned by the userdata
} ChainUD;                    // the "Chain" object (holds the DB)

typedef struct {
    const Block* blk;         // pointer to the current block (no ownership)
} BlockUD;                    // the per‑iteration block wrapper

/* --------------------------------------------------------------
   ----  Metatable helpers  --------------------------------------
   -------------------------------------------------------------- */
#define CHAIN_MT   "BlockSci.Chain"
#define BLOCK_MT   "BlockSci.Block"

/* ---------- Block.__index ------------------------------------------------ */
static int block_index(lua_State* L) {
    BlockUD* u = (BlockUD*)luaL_checkudata(L, 1, BLOCK_MT);
    const char* key = luaL_checkstring(L, 2);
    const Block* b = u->blk;

    if (strcmp(key, "height") == 0) {
        lua_pushinteger(L, (lua_Integer)b->height);
        return 1;
    }
    if (strcmp(key, "hash") == 0) {
        lua_pushlstring(L, (const char*)b->hash.data(), b->hash.size());
        return 1;
    }
    if (strcmp(key, "timestamp") == 0) {
        lua_pushinteger(L, (lua_Integer)b->timestamp);
        return 1;
    }
    // unknown field → nil
    lua_pushnil(L);
    return 1;
}

/* ---------- Chain methods ------------------------------------------------- */
static ChainUD* check_chain(lua_State* L, int idx) {
    return (ChainUD*)luaL_checkudata(L, idx, CHAIN_MT);
}

/* Chain:for_each(cb) ------------------------------------------------------- */
static int chain_for_each(lua_State* L) {
    ChainUD* cu = check_chain(L, 1);
    luaL_checktype(L, 2, LUA_TFUNCTION);          // the user callback

    /* Keep a reference to the callback – cheap (registry entry). */
    lua_pushvalue(L, 2);
    int cb_ref = luaL_ref(L, LUA_REGISTRYINDEX);

    /* Allocate ONE Block userdata that will be reused for every iteration. */
    BlockUD* bu = (BlockUD*)lua_newuserdata(L, sizeof(BlockUD));
    luaL_getmetatable(L, BLOCK_MT);
    lua_setmetatable(L, -1);
    int block_udx = lua_absindex(L, -1);           // remember its stack slot
    lua_pop(L, 1);                                 // leave stack clean

    while (cu->iter->has_next()) {
        const Block& blk = cu->iter->next();
        bu->blk = &blk;                             // update pointer only

        /* Push the callback and the block userdata */
        lua_rawgeti(L, LUA_REGISTRYINDEX, cb_ref); // +1: cb
        lua_pushvalue(L, block_udx);               // +1: block userdata

        /* Call cb(block).  Errors propagate as Lua errors. */
        if (lua_pcall(L, 1, 1, 0) != LUA_OK) {
            const char* err = lua_tostring(L, -1);
            luaL_error(L, "callback error: %s", err);
        }
        /* Optional early‑stop: if the callback returns true, break. */
        int stop = lua_toboolean(L, -1);
        lua_pop(L, 1);                              // discard return value
        if (stop) break;
    }

    luaL_unref(L, LUA_REGISTRYINDEX, cb_ref);
    return 0;   // no Lua values returned
}

/* Chain:map(cb) → Lua array ----------------------------------------------- */
static int chain_map(lua_State* L) {
    ChainUD* cu = check_chain(L, 1);
    luaL_checktype(L, 2, LUA_TFUNCTION);
    lua_pushvalue(L, 2);
    int cb_ref = luaL_ref(L, LUA_REGISTRYINDEX);

    /* Prepare result table */
    lua_newtable(L);
    int result_idx = lua_absindex(L, -1);
    int i = 1;

    BlockUD* bu = (BlockUD*)lua_newuserdata(L, sizeof(BlockUD));
    luaL_getmetatable(L, BLOCK_MT);
    lua_setmetatable(L, -1);
    int block_udx = lua_absindex(L, -1);
    lua_pop(L, 1);

    while (cu->iter->has_next()) {
        const Block& blk = cu->iter->next();
        bu->blk = &blk;

        lua_rawgeti(L, LUA_REGISTRYINDEX, cb_ref); // cb
        lua_pushvalue(L, block_udx);               // block
        if (lua_pcall(L, 1, 1, 0) != LUA_OK) {
            const char* err = lua_tostring(L, -1);
            luaL_error(L, "callback error: %s", err);
        }
        /* Store whatever the callback returned */
        lua_rawseti(L, result_idx, i++);
    }

    luaL_unref(L, LUA_REGISTRYINDEX, cb_ref);
    return 1;   // returns the result table
}

/* Chain:filter(cb) → Lua array of Block userdata -------------------------- */
static int chain_filter(lua_State* L) {
    ChainUD* cu = check_chain(L, 1);
    luaL_checktype(L, 2, LUA_TFUNCTION);
    lua_pushvalue(L, 2);
    int cb_ref = luaL_ref(L, LUA_REGISTRYINDEX);

    lua_newtable(L);
    int result_idx = lua_absindex(L, -1);
    int i = 1;

    BlockUD* bu = (BlockUD*)lua_newuserdata(L, sizeof(BlockUD));
    luaL_getmetatable(L, BLOCK_MT);
    lua_setmetatable(L, -1);
    int block_udx = lua_absindex(L, -1);
    lua_pop(L, 1);

    while (cu->iter->has_next()) {
        const Block& blk = cu->iter->next();
        bu->blk = &blk;

        lua_rawgeti(L, LUA_REGISTRYINDEX, cb_ref); // cb
        lua_pushvalue(L, block_udx);               // block
        if (lua_pcall(L, 1, 1, 0) != LUA_OK) {
            const char* err = lua_tostring(L, -1);
            luaL_error(L, "callback error: %s", err);
        }
        int keep = lua_toboolean(L, -1);
        lua_pop(L, 1);
        if (keep) {
            /* Duplicate the Block userdata (light copy) for the result table */
            lua_pushvalue(L, block_udx);
            lua_rawseti(L, result_idx, i++);
        }
    }

    luaL_unref(L, LUA_REGISTRYINDEX, cb_ref);
    return 1;   // result table
}

/* Chain:reset() – start iteration from the first block again */
static int chain_reset(lua_State* L) {
    ChainUD* cu = check_chain(L, 1);
    cu->iter->reset();
    return 0;
}

/* Chain:close() – free the native iterator (optional, GC will do it) */
static int chain_gc(lua_State* L) {
    ChainUD* cu = (ChainUD*)luaL_checkudata(L, 1, CHAIN_MT);
    delete cu->iter;
    cu->iter = nullptr;
    return 0;
}

/* ---------- Module loader ------------------------------------------------- */
static const luaL_Reg chain_methods[] = {
    {"for_each", chain_for_each},
    {"map",      chain_map},
    {"filter",   chain_filter},
    {"reset",    chain_reset},
    {"close",    chain_gc},
    {NULL, NULL}
};

/* blocksi.open(path) → Chain userdata */
static int blocksi_open(lua_State* L) {
    const char* path = luaL_checkstring(L, 1);
    ChainUD* cu = (ChainUD*)lua_newuserdata(L, sizeof(ChainUD));
    cu->iter = new BlockIterator(path);   // may throw; let Lua see the error
    luaL_getmetatable(L, CHAIN_MT);
    lua_setmetatable(L, -2);
    return 1;   // returns the Chain object
}

/* ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
extern "C" int luaopen_blocksi(lua_State* L) {
    /* Register Block userdata (readonly fields) */
    luaL_newmetatable(L, BLOCK_MT);
    lua_pushcfunction(L, block_index);
    lua_setfield(L, -2, "__index");
    lua_pop(L, 1);   // pop metatable

    /* Register Chain userdata */
    luaL_newmetatable(L, CHAIN_MT);
    lua_pushcfunction(L, chain_gc);
    lua_setfield(L, -2, "__gc");
    luaL_setfuncs(L, chain_methods, 0);
    lua_pop(L, 1);   // pop metatable

    /* Module table */
    lua_newtable(L);
    lua_pushcfunction(L, blocksi_open);
    lua_setfield(L, -2, "open");
    return 1;   // return module table
}
```

### Why this is **fast**  

| Concern | How the stub solves it |
|---------|------------------------|
| **Allocation per block** | Only **one** `Block` userdata is allocated (outside the loop). Inside the loop we merely change the `blk` pointer. |
| **Metamethod look‑ups** | The `__index` metamethod is a tiny C function that directly reads the native `Block` struct; no table copies. |
| **Callback overhead** | The hot loop only does: `push cb`, `push userdata`, `lua_pcall`. This is the cheapest possible bridge between C++ and Lua. |
| **Early termination** | The callback may return `true` to stop early; the loop checks a single boolean after each call. |
| **Garbage‑collection pressure** | The result of `map`/`filter` is a normal Lua table; the only temporaries are the reused userdata and the callback reference (both reclaimed automatically). |
| **Thread‑safety** | All work happens on the same Lua state; the binding does not spawn threads, keeping the Lua VM single‑threaded as usual. |
| **Ease of use** | The API mirrors familiar data‑frame methods (`for_each`, `map`, `filter`) so Python/pandas users feel at home. |

---  

## 3. Building & Testing

```bash
# 1. Save the source as blocksi.c
# 2. Compile (adjust include path for your Lua version)
g++ -std=c++17 -shared -fPIC -O3 \
    -I/usr/include/lua5.4 -o blocksi.so blocksi.c -lstdc++

# 3. Test from Lua
lua - <<'LUA'
local blocksi = require "blocksi"
local chain = blocksi.open("/tmp/dummy_chain")   -- path is ignored in demo

-- Very cheap benchmark: count first 10 000 blocks
local cnt = 0
chain:for_each(function(b)
    cnt = cnt + 1
    if cnt >= 10_000 then return true end   -- early‑stop
end)
print("Iterated", cnt, "blocks")

-- Use map to collect heights of first 5 blocks
local heights = chain:map(function(b) return b.height end)
print("First heights:", table.concat(heights, ", "))

chain:close()
LUA
```

In a real deployment you replace the **fake `BlockIterator`** with the
actual BlockSci iterator (which already knows how to read the on‑disk
indexes). The rest of the binding stays unchanged.

---  

## 4. Extending the API

* **Additional block fields** – just add more `if (strcmp(key, "...") == 0)` cases in `block_index`.
* **Batch callbacks** – expose a `chain:batch(size, cb)` that passes a Lua array of `size` blocks to the callback, further reducing per‑call overhead.
* **Lazy pipelines** – implement a `ChainIter` userdata that supports `:map`, `:filter`, `:collect` chaining, similar to Polars’ lazy API. The core idea stays the same: a single C++ loop driving a series of Lua callbacks while re‑using the same block userdata.

---  

### TL;DR

* **Lua side** – `chain:for_each(cb)` (plus `map`/`filter`) works like pandas/Polars.
* **C side** – a tiny C++ wrapper that iterates, re‑uses one userdata, and calls the Lua function via `lua_pcall`.  
* **Performance** – only a handful of Lua stack operations per block, no heap allocation, early‑stop support, and a clean, idiomatic Lua API.  

Happy hacking! 🚀
